State MSM Profile: Delaware

Background & Methods

In 2015-2016, researchers at Emory University partnered with colleagues at the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) to develop methods to estimate the number of men who have sex with men (MSM) residing in each county in the United States. Using population and housing data from the American Community Survey and estimates from two peer-reviewed publications (Oster et al., 2015 & Purcell et al., 2012), they derived an indirect estimate of MSM population sizes that took into account both the urbanicity of the county as well as its density of households with a male householder and a male same-sex partner.

The full methodology is published in the Journal of Medical Internet Research - Public Health and Surveillance:

Grey JA, Bernstein KT, Sullivan PS, Purcell DW, Chesson HW, Gift TL, Rosenberg ES. Estimating the population sizes of men who have sex with men in US states and counties using data from the American Community Survey. JMIR Public Health Surveill 2016;2(1):e14. DOI: 10.2196/publichealth.5365

Overview of MSM in Delaware

An estimated 13,048 men who have sex with men (MSM) resided in Delaware in 2013, representing 0.3% of the 4,503,084 MSM in the United States. Of the 335,554 adult men of Delaware, 3.9% had had sex with another man in the past 5 years, which was equal to the overall percentage of adult men in the United States who were MSM (3.9%).

Most MSM in Delaware resided in fringe counties of large metropolitan areas (59.8%). Including both central and fringe counties, 59.8% resided in a large metropolitan area.


Percentage of MSM by urbanicity, United States and Delaware, 2013

MSM in Delaware Counties

Among counties or county-equivalent areas in Delaware, New Castle County had the largest population of MSM at 7,808, representing 59.8% of all MSM in the state. Sussex County had the highest percentage of MSM among adult men in Delaware at 5.4%. This was greater than the percentage for Delaware as a whole, which was 3.9% of adult men.

Note: Range cutpoints for the map are based on the distribution of MSM among all counties in the United States.



MSM in Delaware Metropolitan Statistical Areas

Philadelphia-Camden-Wilmington Metropolitan Statistical Area

The Philadelphia-Camden-Wilmington MSA overlaps four states: Delaware, Maryland, New Jersey and Pennsylvania. The Delaware portion of the MSA had the largest metropolitan population of MSM in Delaware at 7,808, or 59.8% of all MSM in the state and 7.8% of the 100,293 MSM in the MSA. Of the 199,553 adult men in the Delaware part of Philadelphia-Camden-Wilmington, an estimated 3.9% were MSM. This was less than the percentage of MSM among adult men in the MSA as a whole, which was 4.6% of adult men (100,293 out of 2,189,761).



Note: Range cutpoints for the map are based on the distribution of MSM among all counties in the United States.




Salisbury Metropolitan Statistical Area

The Salisbury MSA overlaps two states: Delaware and Maryland. The Delaware portion of the MSA had 4,138 MSM, or 31.7% of all MSM in the state and 77.1% of the 5,365 MSM in the MSA. Of 77,187 adult men in the Delaware part of Salisbury, 5.4% were MSM. This was greater than the overall percentage of MSM among adult men in the MSA, which was 3.7% of adult men (5,365 out of 145,918).

Note: Range cutpoints for the map are based on the distribution of MSM among all counties in the United States.




Dover Metropolitan Statistical Area

The Dover MSA had a population of 1,102 MSM, or 8.4% of all MSM in Delaware. Of the 58,814 adult men in Dover, an estimated 1.9% were MSM.

Note: Range cutpoints for the map are based on the distribution of MSM among all counties in the United States.
